  "notes": "West Frisian (Frysk) — the most widely spoken Frisian language, with ~350,000–450,000 speakers in the province of Fryslân (Friesland), Netherlands. Official language alongside Dutch in the province. KEY FEATURES: (1) BREAKING DIPHTHONGS: distinctive centring diphthongs /iə/, /ɪə/, /oə/ from historical long vowels — a hallmark of Frisian. (2) FINAL DEVOICING: voiced obstruents devoiced word-finally and in coda, as in Dutch. (3) /ɡ/ not /ɣ/: West Frisian has a voiced stop /ɡ/ in onset (not the fricative [ɣ] of Dutch). (4) CIRCUMFLEX VOWELS: ⟨â⟩ /ɔː/, ⟨ê⟩ /ɛː/, ⟨ô⟩ /oː/, ⟨û⟩ /yː/ — unique orthographic convention. (5) ⟨y⟩ = /i/ (not a consonant). (6) ⟨u⟩ = /ø/ (front rounded). (7) ANGLO-FRISIAN: shares innovations with English (Anglo-Frisian brightening, nasal loss before fricatives) but diverged after Old Frisian period. (8) Rich vowel system with 12+ monophthongs and multiple diphthongs/centring diphthongs. Sources: Tiersma (1999) *Frisian Reference Grammar*, Visser (1997) *Frysk Wurdboek*, Gorter et al. (2001), Popkema (2006) *Grammatica Fries*.",
